Wash and dry all produce. Core and seed @bell pepper{1}, then slice into ¼-inch-thick strips. Halve, peel, and finely mince @shallot{1}. Thinly slice @garlic{2%cloves}. Cut @roma tomato{1} into eight wedges.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a #medium pan{} over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper and a pinch of @salt{}. Cook, tossing every now and then, until starting to soften, about ~{5%minutes}. Toss in shallot and garlic. Cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}.

Add 4 tomato wedges to pan (save the rest for later) along with 1 TBSP @butter{2%tbsp}, @smoked paprika{2%tsp}, @turmeric{1%tsp}, and @arborio rice{3/4%cup}. Stir to combine and cook until paprika is very aromatic, about ~{30%seconds}.

Carefully pour into pan 1¾ cups water, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, and a few large pinches of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir while scraping up any browned bits on bottom. Bring to a boil and let bubble ~{2%minutes}. Reduce heat to low, give mixture a stir, and cover pan. Let simmer gently for ~{15%minutes}.

After 15 minutes, remove lid from pan and carefully stir in @peas{4%oz}. Place remaining tomato wedges on top of rice mixture. Cover pan and cook without stirring ~{5%minutes} more. Meanwhile, melt 1 TBSP butter in a #small pan{} over medium heat (use a #nonstick pan{} if you have one). Crack in @eggs{2} and cook until whites are set, about ~{3%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Cut @lemon{1} into wedges. Place eggs on top of paella. Serve straight from the pan with lemon wedges for squeezing over.

> When in doubt, put an egg on it! Add fried eggs to paella, and Spain's most famous rice dish instantly becomes even more hearty and filling.

> You can serve this one straight from the pan so everyone at the table can ooh and ahh over this impressive recipe.